reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on December 28, 2023
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars Bad ad, totally appropriate jeans.
reviews.reviewText: The advertisement and photo make you want to avoid these jeans, right? The ad emphasizes “butt lifting” spandex, which must cause modest folks to keep looking elsewhere for their blue jeans.I overheard a stranger at a restaurant raving to her friend about them. The stranger said she got her blue jeans on Amazon and loved them. They didn’t look bad on her, so I got out my phone and found them on Amazon.Upon seeing the ad, I wouldn’t think of buying them for my wife. That big butt photo, and attention called to the “butt lifting” spandex, are poor choices by the advertising professionals. Still, the stranger’s overheard praising and endorsement drew me into buying them for my wife, who needs no butt lifting, thank you very much.My wife now has a pair of comfortable blue jeans that use just the right amount (2%) of spandex. She wore her Christmas gift the day after Christmas, and smiled all day because they fit just right. They conform nicely to her, without being embarrassingly snug. These jeans do look nice and fit well.The advertising suggests the jeans’ spandex do some magic to enhance assets. That likely turns away potential buyers who don’t notice the spandex is only 2%. Only 2% spandex won't cause “spandex cling” that most buyers would find embarrassingly, and uncomfortably, revealing. Only 2% spandex is too insignificant to do that. It will, however, give just the right amount of spandex to comfortably fit, look good, but without looking too tight like in the photo.Bad ad, totally appropriate jeans.
